changes your opinion about the
blowback that we might

00:55:24.800 --> 00:55:27.550
experience as a result
of drone strikes.

00:55:27.550 --> 00:55:33.280
JEREMY SCAHILL: I think the
legacy of what the US did in

00:55:33.280 --> 00:55:36.000
the '70s, '80s in Central
America is still

00:55:36.000 --> 00:55:36.690
felt to this day.

00:55:36.690 --> 00:55:41.160
Right now there's the trial of
Rios Montt in Guatemala.

00:55:41.160 --> 00:55:44.960
And the US was supporting
these murderous juntas.

00:55:44.960 --> 00:55:48.100
And the people have spent
decades trying to get justice

00:55:48.100 --> 00:55:51.020
for what had been lost in the
contra death squads in

00:55:51.020 --> 00:55:53.330
Nicaragua and Battalion
316 in Honduras.

00:55:53.330 --> 00:55:58.110
I think it really sparked a lot
of anti-American hatred.

00:55:58.110 --> 00:56:02.470
Whether or not there was
specific blowback from that, I

00:56:02.470 --> 00:56:04.810
don't know in terms of Americans
being attacked

00:56:04.810 --> 00:56:06.650
inside of the United States.

00:56:06.650 --> 00:56:11.090
I also think that there was a
different mentality in those

00:56:11.090 --> 00:56:13.340
countries then there is in a lot
of Muslim countries around

00:56:13.340 --> 00:56:16.150
the world in terms of
the way that the

00:56:16.150 --> 00:56:17.980
wars are being fueled.

00:56:17.980 --> 00:56:21.400
The US in Central America
was primarily

00:56:21.400 --> 00:56:22.560
working with proxies.

00:56:22.560 --> 00:56:25.720
And with the exception of the
mining of the Nicaraguan

00:56:25.720 --> 00:56:29.860
harbor, where the US had a
guilty verdict against it at

00:56:29.860 --> 00:56:34.690
the World Court for having done
that, the US tried to use

00:56:34.690 --> 00:56:37.430
proxy forces and more
covert presence.

00:56:37.430 --> 00:56:41.070
I think the drones are a great
recruiting tool for al-Qaeda

00:56:41.070 --> 00:56:43.660
or other militant organizations
because it's

00:56:43.660 --> 00:56:44.790
very good branding.

00:56:44.790 --> 00:56:49.560
And so I do fear that we are
giving the perception that

00:56:49.560 --> 00:56:51.350
we're at war with Islam.

00:56:51.350 --> 00:56:53.670
And I think that that is really

00:56:53.670 --> 00:56:56.160
just very, very dangerous.

00:56:56.160 --> 00:56:57.670
Thank you.

00:56:57.670 --> 00:56:58.880
AUDIENCE: Hi, Jeremy.

00:56:58.880 --> 00:56:59.540
Thank you for coming.

00:56:59.540 --> 00:57:02.170
A very quick technical question,
when you mentioned

00:57:02.170 --> 00:57:06.200
Aminah was a covert from the
Catholic to Islam, where did

00:57:06.200 --> 00:57:07.510
you get that information?

00:57:07.510 --> 00:57:09.150
JEREMY SCAHILL: I read
Serbo-Croatian.

00:57:09.150 --> 00:57:10.690
Actually, I can speak
Serbo-Croatian.

00:57:10.690 --> 00:57:15.310
And there was extensive coverage
in the Croatian media

00:57:15.310 --> 00:57:19.510
about who she is and very, very,
very technical details

00:57:19.510 --> 00:57:24.400
about her life and her work and
her conversion to Islam.

00:57:24.400 --> 00:57:25.000
AUDIENCE: I read too.

00:57:25.000 --> 00:57:27.876
So maybe you can tell me later
on which publication that was.

00:57:27.876 --> 00:57:28.220
Thanks.

00:57:28.220 --> 00:57:30.560
JEREMY SCAHILL: Yeah, yeah,
there were a number of exposes

00:57:30.560 --> 00:57:32.230
about her in the local
press in Croatia.

00:57:32.230 --> 00:57:34.395
And in Serbia, there were some
reporting on it as well.

00:57:34.395 --> 00:57:34.740
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:57:34.740 --> 00:57:36.260
JEREMY SCAHILL: Yeah, thanks.

00:57:36.260 --> 00:57:37.320
AUDIENCE: I have
two questions.

00:57:37.320 --> 00:57:40.270
You answered half of the first
one was you consider the

00:57:40.270 --> 00:57:40.910
alternatives.

00:57:40.910 --> 00:57:42.680
And the alternatives you
suggested were to bring him

00:57:42.680 --> 00:57:45.490
here to face our civil
justice system.

00:57:45.490 --> 00:57:48.500
But there may be something else
because that seems to me

00:57:48.500 --> 00:57:52.360
like a very steep battle to
fight or disadvantageous

00:57:52.360 --> 00:57:56.580
battle to fight when you've got
some compelling evidence

00:57:56.580 --> 00:57:58.510
to bring against them.

00:57:58.510 --> 00:58:02.910
And the second one is, as I
travel through Middle East,

00:58:02.910 --> 00:58:05.200
what I see is America
gets the blame and

00:58:05.200 --> 00:58:07.560
this unjustified blame.

00:58:07.560 --> 00:58:11.250
Really what happens is they see
the United States as an

00:58:11.250 --> 00:58:12.960
oppressor when it's really their
own government that's an

00:58:12.960 --> 00:58:17.980
oppressor because the foreign
aid that gets there is

00:58:17.980 --> 00:58:19.630
somewhat diffused.

00:58:19.630 --> 00:58:21.750
It's siphoned off by
the people that

00:58:21.750 --> 00:58:23.760
are powers that be.

00:58:23.760 --> 00:58:28.270
And there doesn't seem to be any
correction for that type

00:58:28.270 --> 00:58:29.260
of activity.

00:58:29.260 --> 00:58:31.680
And that's essentially
what's spawning--

00:58:31.680 --> 00:58:34.820
in my opinion, that's
what spawns this

00:58:34.820 --> 00:58:37.180
anti-American sentiment.

00:58:37.180 --> 00:58:37.950
JEREMY SCAHILL: I
agree with you.

00:58:37.950 --> 00:58:42.900
I mean, I don't necessarily
agree with saying that that's

00:58:42.900 --> 00:58:45.250
the actual thing and that it
has nothing to do with the

00:58:45.250 --> 00:58:46.100
US's actions.

00:58:46.100 --> 00:58:51.660
But I agree strongly with your
sentiment that these regimes--

00:58:51.660 --> 00:58:55.470
the overthrow of Mubarak in
Egypt, for instance, he was a

00:58:55.470 --> 00:59:00.420
widely despised man for what he
had done to his own people.

00:59:00.420 --> 00:59:03.820
But people are also aware that
he stayed in power in part

00:59:03.820 --> 00:59:06.350
because of his tremendous
support from the United States

00:59:06.350 --> 00:59:07.980
through successive
administrations.

00:59:07.980 --> 00:59:11.660
And we've given a lot of
military aid to the

00:59:11.660 --> 00:59:15.460
Jordanians, to the Egyptians, at
times we worked with Bashar

00:59:15.460 --> 00:59:19.580
al-Assad in Syria when it was
convenient for us, the Saudis,

00:59:19.580 --> 00:59:20.390
the Yemenis.

00:59:20.390 --> 00:59:22.880
And I think that it's
a double punch.

00:59:22.880 --> 00:59:25.710
I think people perceive the
United States as being on the

00:59:25.710 --> 00:59:27.960
side of these dictatorships
and not on the side of

00:59:27.960 --> 00:59:29.200
ordinary people.

00:59:29.200 --> 00:59:31.200
I've certainly heard that in the
countries that I've been

00:59:31.200 --> 00:59:33.110
talking about today.

00:59:33.110 --> 00:59:36.595
But I do think though that the
US has a long, or I know that

00:59:36.595 --> 00:59:39.330
the US has a long track record
of bolstering these

00:59:39.330 --> 00:59:41.970
dictatorships, the Bahraini
regime, the Saudis.

00:59:41.970 --> 00:59:44.530
I mean, we are a big part
of that problem.

00:59:44.530 --> 00:59:48.480
But I do think that those
regimes deserve their fair

00:59:48.480 --> 00:59:50.910
share of the blame for what
they've been involved with.

00:59:50.910 --> 00:59:55.620
AUDIENCE: One last thing, US
presence in the Gulf in the

00:59:55.620 --> 01:00:00.840
Middle East during the Iran-Iraq
War was a huge

01:00:00.840 --> 01:00:03.020
stabilizing factor
in the region.

01:00:03.020 --> 01:00:07.740
And as you start to withdraw,
there's all sorts of upheaval

01:00:07.740 --> 01:00:08.710
going on over there.

01:00:08.710 --> 01:00:12.840
So there seems to be
consequences no matter going

01:00:12.840 --> 01:00:14.770
forward or going in reverse.

01:00:14.770 --> 01:00:16.990
There appear to be consequences
either way.

01:00:16.990 --> 01:00:18.920
JEREMY SCAHILL: Well, I
have a little bit--

01:00:18.920 --> 01:00:20.270
you and I could have
a debate club here.

01:00:20.270 --> 01:00:21.670
I have a little bit of a
different take on the

01:00:21.670 --> 01:00:23.130
Iran-Iraq thing.

01:00:23.130 --> 01:00:25.175
Kissinger famously said, we
should arm them both so they

01:00:25.175 --> 01:00:27.070
can kill each other off.

01:00:27.070 --> 01:00:29.160
I think we were a highly
destabilizing presence,

01:00:29.160 --> 01:00:30.970
particularly in Iraq.

01:00:30.970 --> 01:00:34.620
The US was supporting Saddam
Hussein in the '80s when he

01:00:34.620 --> 01:00:36.200
was at his most brutal.

01:00:36.200 --> 01:00:39.880
And Donald Rumsfeld went over
as an envoy in '83 and gave

01:00:39.880 --> 01:00:43.130
Saddam golden cowboy spurs,
a gift from Ronald Reagan.

01:00:43.130 --> 01:00:46.070
And they removed the Iraqi
government from the list of

01:00:46.070 --> 01:00:48.640
state sponsors of terrorism so
that they could sell them

01:00:48.640 --> 01:00:51.390
weapons that were then used to
use chemical weapons on the

01:00:51.390 --> 01:00:53.670
Kurdish population in
the north of Iraq.

01:00:53.670 --> 01:00:58.240
And I think that you can jump in
to history midway and then

01:00:58.240 --> 01:00:59.695
say, well, the US
was stabilizing.

01:00:59.695 --> 01:01:02.320
And the US was a big part of
creating that or making that

01:01:02.320 --> 01:01:05.570
war possible, the
Iran-Iraq War.

01:01:05.570 --> 01:01:09.060
AUDIENCE: I sort of agree with
you to a degree on that.

01:01:09.060 --> 01:01:11.410
JEREMY SCAHILL: Yeah, but your
broader point though about the

01:01:11.410 --> 01:01:13.400
withdrawal, look, in
Afghanistan, I think there are

01:01:13.400 --> 01:01:16.390
pockets of Afghanistan where
people are grateful that the

01:01:16.390 --> 01:01:18.620
United States went in
and got rid of the

01:01:18.620 --> 01:01:19.690
thugs from the Taliban.

01:01:19.690 --> 01:01:20.940
And girls can go to school.

01:01:20.940 --> 01:01:22.940
And women are not living
in constant

01:01:22.940 --> 01:01:25.180
fear of being attacked.

01:01:25.180 --> 01:01:27.270
But then there are large parts
of Afghanistan where the

01:01:27.270 --> 01:01:28.930
Taliban are still in control.

01:01:28.930 --> 01:01:32.310
And there's the added hostility
of US night raids or

01:01:32.310 --> 01:01:33.320
strikes that are happening.

01:01:33.320 --> 01:01:35.610
And they're sort of getting
punched from both sides.

01:01:35.610 --> 01:01:38.130
So I do think that when there's
a withdrawal from

01:01:38.130 --> 01:01:40.850
Afghanistan, there will
be a mixed bag.

01:01:40.850 --> 01:01:43.330
But at the end of day, I think
we have to look back and say,

01:01:43.330 --> 01:01:45.220
what was the point
of any of this?

01:01:45.220 --> 01:01:48.170
I don't know anyone in the
military today, guys that are

01:01:48.170 --> 01:01:50.410
being tasked with fighting the
war, that think that it's a

01:01:50.410 --> 01:01:51.750
good idea to be there.

01:01:51.750 --> 01:01:54.540
I mean, most Americans supported
us going into

01:01:54.540 --> 01:01:56.080
Afghanistan early
on after 9/11.

01:01:56.080 --> 01:01:58.190
At this point, I think the
majority of Americans are sort

01:01:58.190 --> 01:02:00.330
of like, what's the
point of this now?

01:02:00.330 --> 01:02:02.490
Who are we fighting anymore?

01:02:02.490 --> 01:02:04.060
AUDIENCE: I'll try
to make it brief.

01:02:04.060 --> 01:02:07.120
First, thank you very much for
the fantastic reporting and

01:02:07.120 --> 01:02:09.540
all this incredibly dangerous,
hard work you do.

01:02:09.540 --> 01:02:13.120
And sort of related to that,
especially as you've done what

01:02:13.120 --> 01:02:15.450
could be termed kind of exposes
or what would normally

01:02:15.450 --> 01:02:19.190
be called just good
investigative journalism, you

01:02:19.190 --> 01:02:22.670
talk about Blackwater and all
these people and the US

01:02:22.670 --> 01:02:24.320
government and the drone strikes
and things where

01:02:24.320 --> 01:02:26.910
people tend to, I think, believe
they operate sort of

01:02:26.910 --> 01:02:28.410
above the law.

01:02:28.410 --> 01:02:31.670
How much do you actually fear
for your personal safety,

01:02:31.670 --> 01:02:33.980
aside from the people that are
dangerous that you normally--

01:02:33.980 --> 01:02:34.790
JEREMY SCAHILL: Did
Jay Leno put you

01:02:34.790 --> 01:02:35.930
up to this or something?

01:02:35.930 --> 01:02:37.620
AUDIENCE: No, I don't
listen to Jay Leno.

01:02:37.620 --> 01:02:38.056
JEREMY SCAHILL: No.

01:02:38.056 --> 01:02:38.930
I'm just kidding.

01:02:38.930 --> 01:02:41.510
No, he just asked me the same
question on a TV show once.

01:02:41.510 --> 01:02:41.630
AUDIENCE: Oh, really?

01:02:41.630 --> 01:02:42.200
JEREMY SCAHILL: And
it was weird.

01:02:42.200 --> 01:02:43.190
AUDIENCE: Now I feel bad.

01:02:43.190 --> 01:02:45.030
JEREMY SCAHILL: And it scared
my mom to death.

01:02:45.030 --> 01:02:48.280
Why does Jay Leno think
someone's going to kill you?

01:02:48.280 --> 01:02:50.540
I always get embarrassed when
people ask me that.

01:02:50.540 --> 01:02:52.140
And I appreciate your
kind words.

01:02:52.140 --> 01:02:56.100
But I was talking to a colleague
earlier today--

01:02:56.100 --> 01:02:58.200
I mean, there are journalists
that are missing in Syria.

01:02:58.200 --> 01:03:00.580
This young guy who was
a former Marine

01:03:00.580 --> 01:03:01.150
named Austin Tice.

01:03:01.150 --> 01:03:03.710
He's been missing in Syria
for over a year.

01:03:03.710 --> 01:03:07.420
We believe that he's being held
by the Assad government.

01:03:07.420 --> 01:03:09.350
He was a reporter for McClatchy
News Service.

01:03:09.350 --> 01:03:11.190
Record numbers of journalists
are being-- one of the most

01:03:11.190 --> 01:03:14.950
dangerous places on Earth to
be a journalist is Mexico.

01:03:14.950 --> 01:03:17.690
Mexican journalists that report
on the drug cartels are

01:03:17.690 --> 01:03:20.520
just being bumped off and
assassinated left and right.

01:03:20.520 --> 01:03:23.050
Journalists in Somalia are
being murdered by various

01:03:23.050 --> 01:03:25.690
sides of the fighting
factions there.

01:03:25.690 --> 01:03:30.000
And I always get embarrassed
because I live in a nice

01:03:30.000 --> 01:03:31.110
neighborhood in Brooklyn,
New York.

01:03:31.110 --> 01:03:35.690
I live in Park Slope, the land
of lattes and baby strollers

01:03:35.690 --> 01:03:37.320
and double wide baby
strollers.

01:03:37.320 --> 01:03:39.170
And I get to come back.

01:03:39.170 --> 01:03:40.000
And that's where I am.

01:03:40.000 --> 01:03:42.190
And I know that I'm
safe there.

01:03:42.190 --> 01:03:46.310
And so many of our colleagues
that are in these places, they

01:03:46.310 --> 01:03:47.740
live in a constant
state of danger.

01:03:47.740 --> 01:03:51.220
And I always try to recognize
their sacrifice because I

01:03:51.220 --> 01:03:53.210
think they are the actual
heroes of all this.

01:03:53.210 --> 01:03:56.640
It's why my book is dedicated
to journalists locked up for

01:03:56.640 --> 01:03:59.140
doing their job or who died
in pursuit of the truth.

01:03:59.140 --> 01:04:01.300
Because a lot of times
people like me--

01:04:01.300 --> 01:04:02.440
I go on MSNBC.

01:04:02.440 --> 01:04:02.910
And I talk.

01:04:02.910 --> 01:04:03.800
And people know my name.

01:04:03.800 --> 01:04:05.540
And I have a book on the New
York Times Best Seller list.

01:04:05.540 --> 01:04:08.680
And it's like, what about
Abdulelah Haider Shaye, this

01:04:08.680 --> 01:04:11.010
journalist who's in prison
in Yemen in part because

01:04:11.010 --> 01:04:13.240
President Obama told the Yemeni
government he wants him

01:04:13.240 --> 01:04:17.440
locked up for having exposed
a US missile attack?

01:04:17.440 --> 01:04:21.390
I'm no Braveheart.

01:04:21.390 --> 01:04:23.690
My colleagues in Yemen,
Somalia, Syria, Libya,

01:04:23.690 --> 01:04:24.880
everywhere else, those
are the real heroes.

01:04:24.880 --> 01:04:26.920
And we don't know their name
because they're not reporting

01:04:26.920 --> 01:04:27.940
in English necessarily.

01:04:27.940 --> 01:04:29.730
Or they're behind the scenes.

01:04:29.730 --> 01:04:32.820
If I see Thomas Friedman quote
one more time his taxi

01:04:32.820 --> 01:04:34.760
drivers, his concierge, I'm
going to go and shave his

01:04:34.760 --> 01:04:35.880
mustache myself.

01:04:35.880 --> 01:04:38.840
I'm so tired of the sort of
pontificating there because

01:04:38.840 --> 01:04:41.540
there are real journalists
that do serious work.

01:04:41.540 --> 01:04:43.950
And they get almost
no credit for it.

01:04:43.950 --> 01:04:44.920
AUDIENCE: No doubt.

01:04:44.920 --> 01:04:46.780
JEREMY SCAHILL: But thank you
very much for the compliment.

01:04:46.780 --> 01:04:47.603
I appreciate it.

01:04:47.603 --> 01:04:49.495
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

01:04:49.495 --> 01:04:51.480
FEMALE SPEAKER: Jeremy, I just
want to say thank you so much.

01:04:51.480 --> 01:04:53.110
Everybody, if you could give a
round of applause for Jeremy.

01:04:53.110 --> 01:04:53.710
JEREMY SCAHILL: Thank you.

01:04:53.710 --> 01:04:54.310
[APPLAUSE]

01:04:54.310 --> 01:04:54.910
JEREMY SCAHILL: Thank you all.

01:04:54.910 --> 01:04:55.810
Thank you for the
people watching.

01:04:55.810 --> 01:04:58.932
[APPLAUSE]

